<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><title>ludbek</title><link href="http://ludbek.com/" rel="alternate"></link><link href="http://ludbek.com/feeds/tag/pyschology.atom.xml" rel="self"></link><id>http://ludbek.com/</id><updated>2015-03-05T00:00:00+01:00</updated><entry><title>Why We Stare At Eyes</title><link href="http://ludbek.com/blog/why-we-stare-at-eyes/" rel="alternate"></link><updated>2015-03-05T00:00:00+01:00</updated><author><name>ludbek</name></author><id>tag:ludbek.com,2015-03-05:blog/why-we-stare-at-eyes/</id><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;When we talk, see or watch someone we often stare them at their eyes. I believe there are three reasons for this.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;their color distinction is dominant compared to other parts of the face&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;eyes have movement&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;focusing at an eye our brain can get symmetry of entire face&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</summary><category term="eye"></category><category term="pyschology"></category></entry></feed>